People on social media are turning their profile avatars blue and posting blue-themed artwork in memory of 26-year-old Mohamed Mattar, who was killed during an attack by security forces in Sudan at the beginning of June. The hashtag #blueforSudan has been trending internationally on Twitter as people seek to raise broader awareness of the situation in the country. The colour has been chosen because it was the Instagram avatar of Mattar, an engineering graduate. One of those killed yesterday was my friend Mohamed Mattar, a truly stellar human being, the brightest light, and a friend to anyone who met him. pic.twitter.com/7nZ6ClAWgb The internet movement started when Mattarâ€™s friends turned their profile pictures the same colour as the avatar on his mattar77 account. Shahd Khidir, a Sudanese beauty influencer and blogger based in New York who has tens of thousands of Instagram followers, posted about his death last week, helping to widen the reach of the campaign. Itâ€™s really hard being an influencer and sharing information that is â€œoff brandâ€ and not worthy of the â€œfeedâ€ but I cannot hold this in anymore. I am at my office crying because I have so many emotions in me and I feel horrible. Thereâ€™s a massacre happening in my country Sudanâ€™s and a media blackout and internet censorship for four consecutive days. There is no objective media sharing whatâ€™s going on expect for @aljazeeraenglish which had their offices shot down. My friend @mattar77 was MURDERED by the Rapid Support Forces. My best friend was in hiding on June 2 and thatâ€™s the last time I spoke to him. He was missing for 4 days and when I got in touch with him he said: â€œI was caught, beaten and abused and humiliated and arrested and had my phone confiscated from me. I am injured currently.â€ And all I could do this post this. I am sorry to all companies I am running campaigns with but my editorial calendar is currently on pause. I am willing to refund all and everything right away. Please